# Git Commit Rules

## Commit message format
Use conventional commits — always:

```
<type>: <short description in lowercase>
```

| Type | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature or user-facing capability |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `chore` | Maintenance, deps, config (no production code change) |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring with no behavior change |
| `style` | UI-only changes (layout, spacing, colors) |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |

Examples:
```
feat: add saved search alert emails
fix: restore listing hero photo on mobile
style: tighten broker card spacing on team page
chore: update supabase-js to 2.98.0
```

## Workflow
1. Make changes
2. `git add -A` (or stage intentionally — never commit secrets)
3. `git commit -m "type: description"`
4. **`git push origin main` in the same session** — do not leave `main` ahead of `origin/main` with finished work. Matt uses Claude Code and Cursor interchangeably; unpushed commits are invisible to the other tool and are not “shipped.”
5. If the push is non-fast-forward: `git pull --rebase origin main`, resolve, push again.

Pre-commit runs `npm test`. Pre-push runs the full quality gate.

## Bypass hooks (sparingly)
```bash
SKIP_LOCAL_GATES=1 git push      # skip all quality gates
SKIP_DB_GUARD=1 git push         # skip migration drift check only
```

## Branch strategy
- **`main` only.** Pushing to `main` triggers a Vercel production deploy.
- No feature branches, no PRs, **no `git worktree`** — one checkout, one branch. Pre-commit hook at `.git/hooks/pre-commit` rejects commits on any other branch. See `.cursor/rules/always-merge-to-main.mdc`.

## Do NOT
- Commit `.env.local` or any file containing secrets
- Force push to `main`
- Create extra branches or **`git worktree`** checkouts for this repo (trunk-only; see `AGENTS.md`)
- Leave the working tree dirty before switching tasks — always commit or stash
